{#
    ============================================================================
    policy.j2 — PDSNO Core Policy Base Template
    ============================================================================

    PURPOSE
    -------
    This is the base template for policy-related configuration in PDSNO.
    It defines the block structure that user templates can selectively override.

    It covers four policy domains:
        1. security_policy  — ACLs, firewall rules, port security
        2. network_policy   — VLANs, interface assignments, static routes
        3. qos_policy       — Traffic classification, DSCP marking, queuing
        4. custom_policy    — Anything not covered by the blocks above

    RELATIONSHIP TO OTHER TEMPLATES
    --------------------------------
    base_config.j2   — Infrastructure config: NTP, SNMP, syslog, banners.
                        Extend that when you are configuring device infrastructure.

    policy.j2        — THIS FILE. Policy config: ACLs, VLANs, QoS, routing.
                        Extend this when you are pushing a network or security policy.

    policy_template.j2 (roles/policy_deployment/templates/) — Ansible role-level
                        template used directly by the policy_deployment role.
                        That file is for Ansible task execution. This file is for
                        the TemplateEngine Python rendering system. They are
                        separate by design — do not conflate them.

    HOW TO EXTEND THIS TEMPLATE
    ----------------------------
    In your user template (user_{username}_{name}.j2):

        {% extends "policy.j2" %}

        {% block network_policy %}
            {# Your VLAN and interface configuration here #}
            {# All other blocks render as empty — no output unless overridden #}
        {% endblock %}

    You only need to override the blocks relevant to your policy.
    Blocks you do not override produce no output.

    VARIABLES
    ---------
    Required (must be passed to TemplateEngine.render()):
        ansible_network_os    → "ios" | "junos" | "eos"
        inventory_hostname    → device hostname from NIB

    Recommended (used by the header and metadata blocks):
        policy_name           → human-readable policy name (str)
        policy_version        → version string, e.g. "1.2.0" (str)
        policy_owner          → operator account ID who owns this policy (str)
        region                → controller region slug, e.g. "zone-A" (str)
        ansible_date_time     → Ansible datetime fact (dict with .iso8601)

    Policy-domain variables (pass only what your policy needs):

        Network policy:
        vlans               → list of {id, name, description}
        interfaces          → list of {name, type, vlan, description, trunk_vlans}
        static_routes       → list of {network, mask, next_hop, description}

        Security policy:
        acl_rules           → list of {name, sequence, action, protocol,
                                        source, source_wildcard,
                                        dest, dest_wildcard, port}
        port_security       → {max_mac, violation_action, sticky}

        QoS policy:
        qos_classes         → list of {name, dscp, bandwidth_percent, priority}
        qos_policy_name     → name for the service policy (str)

    STRICTNESS NOTE
    ---------------
    The TemplateEngine uses StrictUndefined. Any variable referenced in a block
    you override must either be passed explicitly or use the | default() filter.
    A missing variable is a render error, not a silent empty string.
    This is intentional — silent misconfiguration on network devices is dangerous.

    ============================================================================
#}

{# ── Resolve policy metadata with safe defaults ──────────────────────────── #}
{% set _policy_name    = policy_name    | default("unnamed-policy")  %}
{% set _policy_version = policy_version | default("0.0.0")           %}
{% set _policy_owner   = policy_owner   | default("unset")           %}
{% set _region         = region         | default("unset")           %}
{% set _timestamp      = ansible_date_time.iso8601
    if ansible_date_time is defined
    else "timestamp-unavailable"                %}


{# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    BLOCK: file_header
    A banner comment at the top of the rendered config identifying the policy,
    version, owner, and when it was applied. Override to customise the format.
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
{% block file_header %}
{% if ansible_network_os == 'ios' %}
! ============================================================
! Policy:   {{ _policy_name }}
! Version:  {{ _policy_version }}
! Owner:    {{ _policy_owner }}
! Device:   {{ inventory_hostname }}
! Region:   {{ _region }}
! Applied:  {{ _timestamp }}
! Managed by PDSNO — changes outside this system will be overwritten
! ============================================================
{% elif ansible_network_os == 'junos' %}
# ============================================================
# Policy:   {{ _policy_name }}
# Version:  {{ _policy_version }}
# Owner:    {{ _policy_owner }}
# Device:   {{ inventory_hostname }}
# Region:   {{ _region }}
# Applied:  {{ _timestamp }}
# Managed by PDSNO — changes outside this system will be overwritten
# ============================================================
{% elif ansible_network_os == 'eos' %}
! ============================================================
! Policy:   {{ _policy_name }}
! Version:  {{ _policy_version }}
! Owner:    {{ _policy_owner }}
! Device:   {{ inventory_hostname }}
! Region:   {{ _region }}
! Applied:  {{ _timestamp }}
! Managed by PDSNO — changes outside this system will be overwritten
! ============================================================
{% endif %}
{% endblock %}


{# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    BLOCK: policy_metadata
    Machine-readable metadata embedded as comments for audit log parsing.
    The PDSNO audit trail extracts these fields to correlate rendered configs
    with NIB policy records. Do not remove or rename the key: value format.
    Override only if you need to add fields — do not remove existing ones.
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
{% block policy_metadata %}
{% if ansible_network_os in ['ios', 'eos'] %}
    ! pdsno:policy_name={{ _policy_name }}
    ! pdsno:policy_version={{ _policy_version }}
    ! pdsno:policy_owner={{ _policy_owner }}
    ! pdsno:region={{ _region }}
    ! pdsno:applied={{ _timestamp }}
{% elif ansible_network_os == 'junos' %}
    # pdsno:policy_name={{ _policy_name }}
    # pdsno:policy_version={{ _policy_version }}
    # pdsno:policy_owner={{ _policy_owner }}
    # pdsno:region={{ _region }}
    # pdsno:applied={{ _timestamp }}
{% endif %}
{% endblock %}


{# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    BLOCK: security_policy
    ACL definitions and port security configuration.

    Default: empty — no security config is rendered unless you override this.

    Example override in your user template:

        {% block security_policy %}
        {% if ansible_network_os == 'ios' %}
        {% for rule in acl_rules | default([]) %}
        ip access-list extended {{ rule.name }}
        {{ rule.sequence | default(10) }} {{ rule.action }} {{ rule.protocol }}
        {{ rule.source }} {{ rule.source_wildcard | default('') }}
        {{ rule.dest }} {{ rule.dest_wildcard | default('') }}
        {% if rule.port is defined %} eq {{ rule.port }}{% endif %}
        {% endfor %}
        {% endif %}
        {% endblock %}

    acl_rules list item schema:
        {
        name:             "BLOCK_UNTRUSTED",
        sequence:         10,
        action:           "permit" | "deny",
        protocol:         "ip" | "tcp" | "udp" | "icmp",
        source:           "10.0.0.0" | "any" | "host 10.0.0.1",
        source_wildcard:  "0.0.0.255",     # omit for 'any' or 'host'
        dest:             "192.168.1.0" | "any" | "host 192.168.1.1",
        dest_wildcard:    "0.0.0.255",
        port:             80               # optional, for tcp/udp
        }

    port_security schema:
        {
        max_mac:          2,
        violation_action: "shutdown" | "restrict" | "protect",
        sticky:           true | false
        }
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
{% block security_policy %}{% endblock %}


{# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    BLOCK: network_policy
    VLAN definitions, interface assignments, and static routing.

    Default: empty — no network config is rendered unless you override this.

    Example override in your user template:

        {% block network_policy %}
        {% if ansible_network_os == 'ios' %}
        {% for vlan in vlans | default([]) %}
        vlan {{ vlan.id }}
        name {{ vlan.name }}
        {% endfor %}
        {% for iface in interfaces | default([]) %}
        interface {{ iface.name }}
        description {{ iface.description | default(iface.name) }}
        {% if iface.type | default('access') == 'access' %}
        switchport mode access
        switchport access vlan {{ iface.vlan }}
        {% elif iface.type == 'trunk' %}
        switchport mode trunk
        switchport trunk allowed vlan {{ iface.trunk_vlans | join(',') }}
        {% endif %}
        no shutdown
        {% endfor %}
        {% endif %}
        {% endblock %}

    vlans list item schema:
        { id: 100, name: "Engineering", description: "Engineering VLAN" }

    interfaces list item schema:
        {
        name:         "GigabitEthernet0/1",
        type:         "access" | "trunk",
        vlan:         100,              # for access ports
        trunk_vlans:  [100, 200, 300],  # for trunk ports
        description:  "Uplink to core"
        }

    static_routes list item schema:
        {
        network:     "10.10.0.0",
        mask:        "255.255.0.0",
        next_hop:    "192.168.1.1",
        description: "Route to branch office"   # IOS only
        }
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
{% block network_policy %}{% endblock %}


{# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    BLOCK: qos_policy
    Traffic classification, DSCP marking, and queuing policy.

    Default: empty — no QoS config is rendered unless you override this.

    Example override in your user template:

        {% block qos_policy %}
        {% if ansible_network_os == 'ios' %}
        {% for cls in qos_classes | default([]) %}
            class-map match-any {{ cls.name }}
            match dscp {{ cls.dscp }}
        {% endfor %}
            policy-map {{ qos_policy_name | default('PDSNO-QOS') }}
        {% for cls in qos_classes | default([]) %}
            class {{ cls.name }}
            bandwidth percent {{ cls.bandwidth_percent }}
        {% if cls.priority | default(false) %}priority{% endif %}
        {% endfor %}
        {% endif %}
        {% endblock %}

    qos_classes list item schema:
        {
        name:               "VOICE",
        dscp:               "ef",        # ef, af41, af31, cs3, default
        bandwidth_percent:  20,
        priority:           true         # LLQ — only one class can be priority
        }
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
{% block qos_policy %}{% endblock %}


{# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    BLOCK: custom_policy
    Free-form block for configuration that does not fit the categories above.
    Override this for vendor-specific features, experimental policies, or
    anything else not covered by the structured blocks.

    This block renders last — after security, network, and QoS blocks.
    ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
{% block custom_policy %}{% endblock %}
